> Risotto usually involves a lot of time carefully watching and stirring a pan full of simmering rice, but our chefs found a casserole workaround that makes it a cinch. After giving the meat, rice, and veggies a quick toss in a large pan, the whole thing is sprinkled with cheese and transferred to the oven, where it bakes its way to creamy, al dente perfection.

Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to upper position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Halve and peel @yellow onion{1}, then dice into ¼-inch pieces. Halve @tomato{1}, then dice into roughly ¼-inch pieces. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Chop @kale{8%ounce} into smaller, bite-size pieces.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat (use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Add @ground pork{20%ounce} and @Tuscan Heat Spice{2%tablespoon}, breaking up meat into pieces. Cook until lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}. Toss in onion and garlic, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until onion is just softened, about ~{2%minutes}.

Stir tomato and @tomato paste{3%tablespoon} into pan and season with salt and pepper. Stir in kale in batches, allowing each batch to wilt before adding more (don't overcrowd the pan). Continue to cook, stirring, until kale is fully wilted, about ~{2%minutes}.

Stir @Arborio rice{1.5%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{2}, and 2 1/2 cups water into pan. Bring to a boil, then stir in @butter{1%tbsp}. Remove from heat.

Lightly butter a #baking dish{}(we used 9 x 13-inch). Transfer mixture in pan to buttered dish. Sprinkle evenly with @Parmesan cheese{1/2%cup} and @Italian cheese blend{1%cup}. Cover dish tightly with #aluminum foil{}. Bake in oven until liquids are absorbed and rice is tender, ~{16-18%minutes}. Meanwhile, trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}.

Remove foil from casserole and sprinkle with scallions. Return to oven and bake, uncovered, until cheese is lightly browned, ~{3-4%minutes} more.

> For an extra crispy top, place casserole under broiler and broil for about 3 minutes.

Divide between plates and serve.